07024nam a22010695i 9783110661996DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192019miu    fo  d z      eng d  a97831106619967 a10.1515/97831106619962doi  a(DE-B1597)522282  a(OCoLC)1100431242  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amiucUS-MI 7aHIS0370102bisacsh00aBlind Spots of Knowledge in Shakespeare and His World :bA Conversation /ced. by Subha Mukherji. 1aKalamazoo, MI : bMedieval Institute Publications, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (226 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Medieval and Early Modern Culture ,x0085-6878 ;v6500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Blind Spots of Knowledge in Shakespeare and His World -- tEssays and Responses -- t1. Baffling Terms -- tBaffling Comedy, Baffling Ourselves: A Response to Adam Zucker -- tKnowing Games: A Response to Adam Zucker -- t2. Shakespeare’s Nuts: The Blind Spots of the Edible Contact Zone -- tFlying Blind, Going Nuts: A Response to Jonathan Gil Harris -- t3. Eyes Wide Shut: Seeing and Knowing in Othello -- tSeeing Blindness: A Response to Supriya Chaudhuri -- tTowards an Epistemology of the Stage? A Response to Supriya Chaudhuri -- t4. What Emilia Knew: Shakespeare Reads James -- tMinding Shakespeare’s Gaps: A Response to Aveek Sen -- tDarkness Visible: A Response to Aveek Sen -- t5. Knowing Kin and Kind in The Winter’s Tale -- tUnknowing Kind: A Response to Tanya Pollard -- tDifficult Loves: A Response to Tanya Pollard -- t6. The Epistemology of Violence in The Comedie of Errors -- tWhat Does the Slave Know? A Response to Stephen Spiess -- tNarrating Violence: A Response to Stephen Spiess -- t7. Broken English: A Dialogue -- t“To sleep, maybe to dream” and Other Encounters with a Trained Machine -- tThe Inheritance of Meat -- t8. Conscience Doth Make Errors: The Blind Spot of Shakespearean Quotation -- tOn Not Knowing Shakespeare: A Response to Zachary Lesser -- tThe Food of Points: A Response to Zachary Lesser -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA "blind spot" suggests an obstructed view, or partisan perception, or a localized lack of understanding. Just as the brain "reads" the "blind spot" of the visual field by a curious process of readjustment, Shakespearean drama disorients us with moments of unmastered and unmasterable knowledge, recasting the way we see, know and think about knowing. Focusing on such moments of apparent obscurity, this volume puts methods and motives of knowing under the spotlight, and responds both to inscribed acts of blind-sighting, and to the text or action blind-sighting the reader or spectator. While tracing the hermeneutic yield of such occlusion is its main conceptual aim, it also embodies a methodological innovation: structured as an internal dialogue, it aims to capture, and stake out a place for, a processive intellectual energy that enables a distinctive way of knowing in academic life; and to translate a sense of intellectual "community" into print.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aBlinder Fleck. 4aFrühe Neuzeit. 4aOrientierungslosigkeit. 4aShakespeare. 4aWissen. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBlind Spots.  aEarly Modern literature.  aShakespeare.  ablind-sighting.  adisorientation.  aknowability.  aknowing.1 aChaudhuri, Supriya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Jonathan Gil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHope, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesser, Zachary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l